It was a bright and sunny summer day when we arrived at this point, with a clear view of the reservoir.  We wanted to see what we could get; this nearly became a stationary count.  The Bald Eagle, of course, made the visit exciting - it was a full adult.  No nesting activity discerned, though.  The same cannot be said for the Western Kingbirds, who appeared to be engaged in nest building, and the American Coots, who had a baby on the other side of the reservoir from them!  This area is just above one of my Burrowing Owl survey territories.

LOCALITY: Airport Rd/Willow Creek Rd/Sylvia Rd/York Rd
TRIP COMMENTS: cold and clear.  Birding with Ed P. here we wandered the country roads (Ager, York, Airport, Willow Cr, Sylva, Snowden Hovey Gulch and Little Shasta Rd) and grasslands surrounding the cattle ranches. Checking all the fence lines, poles, and fields yielded: MERLIN, PRAIRIE FALCON, BALD EAGLE, harriers, 2 L. SHRIKES, a number of BB MAGPIES, & 4 MOUNTAIN BLUEBIRDS. Throughout our drive we checked out the ranch ponds for wintering ducks. The best pond was found along Sylva RD which had: 2 HOODED MERGANSERS, a CACKLING GOOSE, RN DUCKS, more Lesser Scaup & Bufflehead. Other ponds also included AMERICAN WIGEON & Gadwall.
